signs/sfu/css/thickbox.css\" media=\"screen\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\"/>\n<link href=\"/content/dam/sfu/computing/css/compsci.css\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\"/>\n<script src=\"//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.4.4/jquery.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n<script src=\"/etc/designs/sfu/js/scripts.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n<script src=\"/etc/designs/sfu/js/common.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n<style type=\"text/css\">#banner a { background-image: url(\"/content/dam/sfu/computing/banners/logo_compsci.png\") } </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n<div id=\"container\">\n<div id=\"banner\">\n<a href=\"//www.sfu.ca\">Simon Fraser University</a>\n</div>\n<div id=\"globalNav\">\n<ul id=\"campuses\">\n<li class=\"sfu\"><a href=\"//www.sfu.ca\">sfu.ca</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.burnaby.sfu.ca\">Burnaby</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.surrey.sfu.ca/\">Surrey</a></li>\n<li class=\"last\"><a href=\"http://www.vancouver.sfu.ca/\">Vancouver</a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul id=\"services\">\n<li class=\"dropdown\" id=\"online\">\n<a class=\"tabs\" href=\"//www.sfu.ca/onlineservices/\">SFU Online</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"dropdown\" id=\"directory\">\n<a class=\"tabs\" href=\"//www.sfu.ca/dir/\">A-Z Links</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"last\" id=\"search\">\n<form action=\"//www.sfu.ca/search.html\" class=\"search\" method=\"get\">\n<input id=\"s\" name=\"q\" type=\"text\" value=\"Search sfu.ca\"/>\n<span class=\"button\"><input id=\"submit\" type=\"submit\" value=\"Search\"/></span>\n</form>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"leftnav left_navigation\">\n<div id=\"nav\">\n<ul id=\"CMPT128InfoMenu\">\n<li><a class=\"highlight\" href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/index.html\">CMPT 275 Home</a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/contacts.html\">Contacts</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/AcadHon.html\">Academic Honesty</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/exams.html\">Grading Exam dates</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/notes.html\">Notes, Class Schedule</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/Voting_Project.html\">Project specification </a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/assign.html\">Deliverable descriptions and dates</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/assignstand.html\">Deliverable Preparation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/teamsel.html\">team selection and team conflict resolution</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/morelinks.html\">Tutorials and Useful links for implementation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/Hypermail/cmpt-275/\">Mail Archive</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/view.html\">Outline E100</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://courses.cs.sfu.ca/\">Course Management</a></li>\n</ul>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n<ul><li class=\"highlight\"><a href=\"/computing.html\">Computing Science Home</a></li></ul><ul>\n<li><a href=\"/contact-us.html\">Contact Us</a>\n</li><li class=\"rule\">Â </li>\n<li><a href=\"/about.html\">About Computing Science</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/undergraduate.html\">Undergraduate Students</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/graduateprogram.html\">Graduate students</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/research.html\">Research</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/industryrelations.html\">Industry Relations</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/people.html\">People</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/newsandevents.html\">News &amp; Events</a></li>\n<li class=\"rule\">Â </li><li><a href=\"https://intraweb.cs.sfu.ca/\">Intranet</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://portal.cs.sfu.ca/\">Portal</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div id=\"content_2col\">\n<div class=\"parsys main_content\">\n<div class=\"text\">\n<ul><li>\n<br/><span style=\"font-size: 9pt;\"><a href=\"/CC/\">Course Central</a> &gt; \n					<a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/index.html\">CMPT 275</a> &gt; </span>\n<a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/Voting_Project.html\">Project description</a> <br/>\n<center>\n<hr noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"6\" width=\"100%\"/>\n<h1>CMPT 275: Software Engineering I\n						<br/>SPRING 2012</h1>\n<hr noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"6\" width=\"100%\"/>\n<h1>Project: Voting Tabulation and Election Result Determination System</h1>\n<hr noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"6\" width=\"100%\"/>\n</center>\n<h2><u>Project Description</u></h2>\n					When British Columbians voted in the provincial election in May 2005 they also \n					voted in a referendum to decide if British Columbia\'s electoral system should be \n					changed to the single transferable vote. At that time the referendum was narrowly defeated.\n					We will assume that this referendum  \n					passed and that British Columbia was moving to the single transferable vote\n					as proposed by the British Columbia citizens\' assembly (see \n					 <a href=\"http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca/public\">STV</a> for details). \n					<br/>Your team is subcontracting for ABC software consultants. ABC software \n					consultants have just received the contract to develop the software to support \n					the new STV electoral system. The software must:\n					<ul>\n<li>Allow \"electoral officials\"  to add and modify riding information for existing ridings, and to add new ridings. Such changes and additions\n						can only be made before an election</li>\n<li>Allow  \"returning officers\"  to tabulate the results, from paper ballots collected at each polling station into a  ballot\n						listing file. This can only be done during an election</li>\n<li>Allow  \"returning officers\" to perform a recount for a particular riding, from paper ballots collected at each polling \n						station in that riding, into a ballot recount listing file. This can only be done after an election</li>\n<li>Allow \"returning officers\" to add tabulated votes from a particular poll (ballot listing files) to the results for the \n						riding containing that poll. This can only be done during an election or a recount</li>\n<li>Determine who has been elected in a riding from the combined results of all polls in that riding. This determination can \n						be made during an election or after the  election is complete.</li>\n<li>Determine who would be elected in a riding if no one else voted, from the combined results of all polls in that riding.\n						This determination can be made during an election.</li>\n<li>Provide \"electoral officials\" and \"reporters\" with selected information, results and statistics for any number of \n						selected ridings at any time during the election</li>\n<li>Provide \"electoral officials\" and \"reporters\" with predictions of likely winners for any number of selected ridings\n						 at any time during the election</li>\n<li>Determine who has been elected from the combined results of all polls in a riding</li>\n<li>Provide complete election results for all ridings to the \"electoral officials\" after the election.</li>\n<li> Tabulate and display results for the local riding on local networks of workstations at each polling station. </li>\n<li> Tabulate and display results for the entire province at a central \"election results center\"</li>\n<li> Each of these locations will have access for all types of users</li>\n<li> Results will periodically be securely communicated between the polling stations in a riding </li>\n<li> Results will periodically be securely communicated from the polling stations in a riding to the \"election results center\" <br/>  \n					\n					To facilitate these tasks, your software system will perform three major functions:<br/>\n<ul>\n<li>A persistent (available whenever software is run) riding repository which contains information about each riding</li>\n<li>A system or systems to calculate and display election results and predictions and display riding information from the repository.</li>\n<li>A vote tabulation system to accept ballot information from \"returning officers\" counting votes.</li>\n</ul> \n					\n					Your software system\'s first major function is concerned with the <u>riding repository</u>.\n					An \"electoral official\" stores or updates information about the ridings in  the riding repository before an election.  \n					The \"returning officer\" stores vote information in the riding repository during an election. The \"electoral official\" \n					and the \n					\"reporter\" access information from the repository during an election. The \"electoral official\" accesses the results of the\n					election from the repository after the election. The information stored will include:\n					<ul>\n<li> A map of the riding stored in a file in .gif or .jpeg format</li>\n<li>Values of keywords used by the \"electoral official\"  to describe each riding. The \"electoral official\" and the \"reporter\" need to\n						be able to search for ridings and extract information about those ridings based on the values of one or more of these keywords. The keywords\n						that you must have are:\n						<ul>\n<li>Name of the riding</li>\n<li>number of voters in the riding</li>\n<li>date riding was created</li>\n<li>Number of seats to be filled in the riding</li>\n<li>Number of candidates running in the riding</li>\n<li>Number of incumbents in the riding</li>\n<li>Name and party affiliation of candidates</li>\n<li>Name and party affiliation of incumbent MLAs</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Different users have different levels of access to this data at different times:\n						<ul>\n<li>The \"electoral officials\"  must be able to create new keywords, and delete keywords \n							that have been added by any \"electoral official\". This cannot be done during an election</li>\n<li>The \"Electoral officials\" and \"reporters\" must be able to search for ridings\n							based on any combination of added and basic keywords or combinations of the \n							added or basic keywords. \"Reporters\" can only search during the election, \"Electoral Officials can search at any time</li>\n<li>The \"electoral officials\" and \"reporters\" must be able to extract and display selected information \n							from the any subset of ridings chosen by a search for ridings</li>\n<li>The \"returning officer\" can associate the \"counted votes\" (more specifically first,\n							second, third ... choice on each counted ballot) with the riding during the election or recount. </li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<br/>\n					Your software system\'s second major function is concerned with the <u>calculation\n					and presentation of election results and presentation of riding information</u>. The \"reporter\" or \n					\"electoral official\" must be able to retrieve election results for selected ridings at any time during the election.\n					From the retrieved riding data, your system should create new riding summaries containing\n					up to date information for each selected riding. This information must include any user selected subset of the following\n					<ol>\n<li> a map of the riding</li>\n<li> the voter turnout </li>\n<li> the keyword values associated with the riding</li>\n<li> the number of first choice votes for each candidate in the riding</li>\n<li> the list of candidates that would be elected if no one else voted and their party affiliations</li>\n<li> the list of any candidates that have been elected and their party affiliations</li>\n<li> Graphs showing each of the following:</li>\n<li><ul>\n<li> the number of first choice votes for each of the candidates in the riding</li>\n<li> the number of votes transferred from each elected candidate to their opponents </li>\n<li> the number of votes transferred from each eliminated candidate to their opponents\n							(for predictions and final results only)</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ol> \n					The \"reporter\" and the \"electoral official\" must be able to choose which information and graphs will be included in their riding summaries.\n					The \"reporter\" and the \"electoral official\" must also be able to give the summary a title and save it to removable disk. \n					The \"reporter\" can generate summaries only during the election. The \"electoral official\" can generate summaries during and after the \n					election. \n					The \"electoral official\" must also be able to generate and save a list of the\n					elected candidates in all ridings after the election has been completed. \n					\n					<br/><br/>Your software system\'s third major function is the \n					<u> vote tabulation system</u>. The vote tabulation system accepts ballot information from \n					\"returning officers\" counting votes. The contents of each paper ballot, cast at a particular poll, are\n					input by the \"returning officers\" into a ballot listing for that poll. The ballot information \n					and the accuracy of the \"returning officer\" entering the data must be validated by a second\n					independent \"returning officer\" and confirmed by a third \"returning officer\". You must be able to save ballot listings\n					to removable media and load ballot listing from removable media into your system.\n					The ballot listing for the poll can then be added to the results\n					for the riding in which that poll is located. A particular ballot listing can only be added to the \n					results once. Once the ballot listing for a particular poll has been added to the results for the\n					riding in which that poll resides those ballots are available to be part of the determination of\n					who is to be elected in that riding.    \n					<br/>\n					Here is an example describing how a \"reporter\" may use this voting tabulation and election \n					result determination system. A \"reporter\" might wish to display the number of first choice votes for\n					each candidate in all ridings that had at least one incumbent MLA who was a \n					member of the NDP party. The \"reporter\" would create\n					a riding summary by first selecting all the desired ridings from the riding\n					repository. The \"reporter\" will then select which of the available pieces\n					of information or graphics she/he wanted to include in her/his riding summaries.\n					Then the selected information from all the selected ridings would be combined into a \n					set of riding summaries.  Finally, the \"reporter\" might save the newly created riding summaries,\n					as a file called \"Ridings_with_a_NDP_incumbent\". \n					<br/>\n					As you can gather, there are three ways of using the Voting tabulation and election result determination system,\n					each with a different type of user in mind. \n					<ul>\n<li>The first way of using the system \n						is related to the population of the riding repository with information describing \n						the ridings and the production of riding descriptions. The intended user \n						is the \"electoral official\". </li>\n<li>The second way of using the system is related \n						to the viewing of the riding information at any time by the \"electoral official\", the viewing of counted vote statistics \n						at any time during the election by the \"reporter\" or the \"electoral official\" and the viewing of counted vote statistics \n						after the election or during a recount by the \"electoral official\". Care must be \n						put into the design of the \"viewing\" function of the voting tabulation and election result determination system so \n						that it is simple and flexible for the \"reporter\" or \"electoral official\"  to utilize. \n						The \"reporter\" or \"electoral official\" should be able to choose any subset of the available\n						riding information or graphical representations of results when requesting the most recent election\n						results or riding information. </li>\n<li>The third way of using the system is related to the \n						entering of counted votes. Its intended user is the \"returning officer\". The \n						\"returning officer\" may tabulate votes for any poll at any time during the election, and add tabulated\n						votes to the riding information at any time during the election. </li>\n</ul>\n					\n					The Voting Tabulation and Election Result Determination System must run on the Windows platform, \n					and be developed using Java or C++.  Any persistent data should be stored in a MS SQL database or a custom designed data solution.\n					Code should be developed using the \n					coding standard summarized at <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/docs/codeconv/\">JAVA CODING STANDARD</a> or \n					<a href=\"http://google-styleguide.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/cppguide.xml\">C++ CODING STANDARD</a>\n<hr noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"6\" width=\"100%\"/>\n<center>\n<b>*</b> <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/275/jregan/\">CMPT 275 Information Page</a>\n<b>*</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CourseCentral/\">Course Central</a>\n<b>*</b>\n<a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/\">Computing Science Home</a>\n<b>*</b>\n<br/>Janice Regan, last modified January 12, 2012. \n					</center>\n</li></ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div id=\"footer\">\n<ul>\n<li>8888 University Drive, Burnaby, B.C. Canada V5A 1S6</li>\n<li><a href=\"//www.sfu.ca/webmaster/terms.html\">Terms / Privacy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"//www.sfu.ca/contact/index.html\">Contact SFU</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"//www.sfu.ca/about/sitemap.html\">SiteMap</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"//www.sfu.ca/security/sfuroadconditions/\">Road Conditions</a></li>\n<li>Â© Simon Fraser University</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<script src=\"/etc/clientlibs/foundation/main.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n<script src=\"/etc/designs/sfu/js/jquery.thickbox.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">\n\n\n\n  var _gaq = _gaq || [];\n\n  _gaq.push([\'_setAccount\', \'UA-2520725-16\']);\n\n  _gaq.push([\'_trackPageview\']);\n\n\n\n  (function() {\n    var ga = document.createElement(\'script\'); ga.type = \'text/javascript\'; ga.async = true;\n    ga.src = (\'https:\' == document.location.prot