nd contact info.\">Office Hours and Emails</a></li>-->\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"CourseOutline.html\" title=\"Course description, learning outcomes, textbooks, structure and evaluation, etc..\">Course Outline</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"LectureNotes.html\" title=\"Some of the material used during lectures.\">Partial Lecture Notes</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"Assignments.html\" title=\"Description of each assignment.\">Assignments</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"Links.html\" title=\"Links to all sort of fun stuff!\">Links</a> </li>\n</ul>\n<!-- MAIN -->\n<div id=\"main\">\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Office Hours</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\">\n<ul class=\"ul-box\">\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Instructor</span>: Anne Lavergne\r\n			<ul>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Office</span>: TASC1 9227\r\n					<ul>\n<!--			<li><a href=\"SFU_ASB_map.pdf\">Where are ASB and TASC 1</a> (Applied Science Building and Technology And Science Complex 1)? \r\n							On this map, ASB is indicated by a red rectangle and TASC 1 is number 7a.</li> -->\n<li><a href=\"sfu_campus_map.pdf\">Where is Anne\'s office in TASC 1</a> (Technology and Science Complex 1)? \r\n		<!--			    On this map, TASC 1 is located at cells S45/T45 to S48/T48.-->\r\n							My office is located at cell T47.</li>\n<li><a href=\"Where_is_my_office.pdf\">Where is Anne\'s office?</a> Not the best, but it will have to do. :)</li>\n<li><a href=\"ASB_CSIL_map.pdf\">Where is Anne\'s office in relation to CSIL</a> (Computing Science Instructional Lab)?				\r\n<!--						On this map, the room the TA uses for office hours is located in ASB 9838, which is indicated by a red rectangle.\r\n-->\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Office hours - in my office TASC 1 9227</span>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"inner-box\">Wednesday - 13:30 to 15:30</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">TA</span>: Shuyang (Samuel) Sun\r\n			<ul>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Office hours:</span>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"inner-box\">Monday - in room ASB9838_TA_3 (in CSIL), from 12:00-14:00</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"box-content\">Please, respect these office hours. If you cannot come to any of the above office hours, \r\n		please make an appointment with the instructor or the TA via email.</p>\n</div>\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Email</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\">\n<ul class=\"ul-box\">\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"email\">cmpt-363@sfu.ca</span>\n<p class=\"item-content\">Used by the instructor to broadcast messages to all students registered to Cmpt 363. \r\n			The TA and the instructor also receive a copy of the broadcasted message. \r\n			Emails are sent to your <em>username</em>@sfu.ca.</p>\n<p class=\"item-content\">These broadcasts are archived <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CC/Hypermail/cmpt-363/\">here!</a></p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"email\">cmpt-363-help@sfu.ca</span>\n<p class=\"item-content\">Used by the students to send questions to the TA. The instructor also receive a copy of the email.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"email\">alavergn@cs.sfu.ca</span>\n<p class=\"item-content\">To be used by students for <em>administrative</em> matter only.</p>\n<p class=\"item-content\">Please, note that I do not answer emails during the week-ends.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Instructions</span>: When sending email...\r\n			<ul>\n<li class=\"inner-box\">In the subject line, include:\r\n					<ul>\n<li>Course # + the topic of the message</li>\n<li>For example: \"Cmpt 363 - missed midterm due to illness\"</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"inner-box\">In the body of your message, include:\r\n					<ul>\n<li>Student name</li>\n<li>Student number</li>\n<li>Student account (username)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<!-- FOOTER -->\n<div id=\"footer\">\n<p class=\"footer-text\">Copyright Â© <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/\">School of Computing Science</a>,\r\n\r\n <a href=\"http://www.sfu.ca/\">Simon Fraser University</a>, \r\n\r\n <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/fas-info/cs/people/Faculty/Profile/alavergn.html\">Anne Lavergne</a> - Spring 2013 - This web site is \r\n  constantly being modified, so keep an eye on it!</p>\n</div>\n</body>\n</html>\n','2013-04-01 05:15:53.115604'),('http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CourseCentral/363/alavergn/CourseOutline.html','CMPT 363 - User Interface Design','<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN\"\r        \"http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd\">\n <html lang=\"en\" xml:lang=\"en\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"> <head> <title>CMPT 363 - User Interface Design</title> <link href=\"CSS files/basic.css\" id=\"basic-style\" media=\"print,screen,projection\" rel=\"stylesheet\" title=\"Basic Style\" type=\"text/css\"/> <link href=\"Images/favicon.ico\" rel=\"icon\" type=\"image/x-icon\"/> <meta content=\"Anne Lavergne\" name=\"author\"/> <meta content=\"text/css\" http-equiv=\"Content-Style-Type\"/> </head> <body> <!-- HEADER --> <div id=\"header\"> <h1>Computing Science - Spring 2013</h1> <h2>CMPT 363 - User Interface Design</h2> <h3>Instructor: Anne Lavergne</h3> <h4>Simon Fraser University</h4> <h4>Email: <span class=\"email\">alavergn@cs.sfu.ca</span></h4> </div>\n<!-- MENU --> <ul id=\"menuList\">\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"index.html\" title=\"Our home: Instructor and TA office hours and contact info.\">Home</a></li>\n<!--<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"index.html\" title=\"Our home: the latest news and announcements.\">News</a></li>-->\n<!--<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"Admin.html\" title=\"Instructor and TA\'s offcie hours and contact info.\">Office Hours and Emails</a></li>-->\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"CourseOutline.html\" title=\"Course description, learning outcomes, textbooks, structure and evaluation, etc..\">Course Outline</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"LectureNotes.html\" title=\"Some of the material used during lectures.\">Partial Lecture Notes</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"Assignments.html\" title=\"Description of each assignment.\">Assignments</a></li>\n<li class=\"menuAdmin\"> <a href=\"Links.html\" title=\"Links to all sort of fun stuff!\">Links</a> </li>\n</ul> <!-- MAIN -->\n<div id=\"main\">\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Description</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\">\n<ul class=\"ul-box\">\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Course Name</span>: User Interface Design</li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Course Web Site:</span> http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CourseCentral/363/alavergn/index.html</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Course Credits</span>: 3 credits</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Calendar Objective/Description</span>:\r		<p class=\"item-content\">This course provides a comprehensive study of user interface design. Topics include: goals and \r		principles of UI design (systems engineering and human factors), historical perspective, current paradigms (widget-based, \r		mental model, graphic design, ergonomics, metaphor, constructivist/iterative approach, and visual languages) and their evaluation, \r		existing tools and packages (dialogue models, event-based systems, prototyping), future paradigms, and the social impact of UI.</p></li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Instructor\'s Objectives</span>:\r		<p class=\"item-content\">This course introduces students to the art and science of designing usable human-computer interfaces. \r		After exploring the way we interact with everyday things, we shall move our attention to the way we interact with computers. \r		In our explorations, we will discuss concepts such as visibility, affordance, mental models, interaction, interface, usability, etc. \r		We will also take a close look at the process of designing human-computer interfaces using a user-centred approach. Through individual \r		and team work, students will gain experience in the phases of this process: gathering requirements, designing, prototyping and \r		evaluating the usability of human-computer interfaces.</p> </li>\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Prerequisites</span>: CMPT 225</li>\n</ul> </div> <h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Instructor</span></h2> <div class=\"h2-box\"> <ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Instructor</span>: Anne Lavergne</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Office</span>: TASC1 9227</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Email</span>: alavergn@cs.sfu.ca</li> </ul> </div>\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Learning Outcomes</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\"> <ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">At the end of this course, we will ...</span>:\r			<ul>\n<li>Have become aware of our interaction with \"things\" â€¦\r					<ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li>When the interaction with a \"thing\" is satisfying (when a \"thing\" is usable, i.e., allows us to easily do the task it \r						    is designed for)</li> <li>When the interaction with a \"thing\" is frustrating (when a \"thing\" is not usable, i.e., it does not allow us \r						    to easily do the task it is designed for)</li> </ul> </li> <li>Be able to discuss the reason(s) why the interaction with a \"thing\" is either satisfying or frustrating \r				    (using design principles)</li> <li>And when it is frustrating, be able to propose solutions</li> <li>Have changed our attitude towards building \"things\" (focus on user)</li> <li>Be able to develop usable human-computer interfaces				\r					<ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li>Gather requirements using various techniques: know the users (may have diverse needs), their tasks, \r						    the domain and environment in which they do their tasks</li> <li>Design a simple user interface, using an iterative, user-centred approach</li> <li>Describe the role of prototyping (in requirements gathering, design and evaluation) and create \r						    various prototypes, selecting the type of prototype appropriate to each phase in the development process</li> <li>Evaluate human-computer interfaces using a variety of evaluation techniques</li> </ul> </li> </ul> </li> </ul>\n</div>\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Structure</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\">\n<ul class=\"ul-box\">\n<li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Lecture day, time, and location: </span> Tuesday, 4:30 until 7:20pm in AQ 3003</li> <li class=\"box-item\">Late arrivals are disruptive i.e., disrespectful to all already in the class. Please, come ***on time***.</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Lecture Topic Overview</span>: \r\n			<ul>\n<li>Interaction between humans and everyday things, as well as computers</li> <li>Concepts such as visibility, affordance, feedback, metaphors, mental models and usability models</li> <li>Iterative human-centred approach to design and development process</li> <li>User, task and environment analysis</li> <li>Design methods and guidelines</li> <li>Prototyping methods</li> <li>Interaction styles and interface technologies</li> <li>Usability evaluation and evaluation methods</li>\n</ul> </li> </ul> </div> <h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Evaluation</span></h2> <div class=\"h2-box\"> <ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Course Evaluation</span>: \r			<p class=\"item-content\">Students\' final mark for this course will be calculated using the following course evaluation scheme:</p> <ul> <li>10% for 3 assignments\r					<ul> <li>Assignment 0 -&gt; 1% â€“ to be done individually</li> <li>Assignment 1 -&gt; 4% â€“ to be done in team</li> <li>Assignment 2 -&gt; 5% â€“ to be done in team</li> </ul> </li> <li>20% for final project â€“ to be done in team\r					<ul> <li>Part 1 -&gt; 8%</li> <li>Part 2 -&gt; 12%</li> </ul> </li> <li>30% for Midterm 1 â€“ to be done individually</li> <li>40% for Midterm 2 â€“ to be done individually</li> <li>There shall be ***no*** final exam for this course.</li> </ul> <p class=\"item-content\">Students must attain an overall passing grade (50%) on the weighted average of exams in the course in order to obtain \r			   a clear pass: a grade of C- or better.</p> <p class=\"item-content\">The instructor reserves the right to modify the course grading scheme.</p> </li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Examination Schedule:</span>:\r			<ul> <li>Midterm 1 - Week 7 - Tuesday, February 26, sometimes between 4:30 and 7:20, location: AQ 3003 and AQ 3005</li> <li>Midterm 2 - Week 13 - Tuesday, April 9, sometimes between 4:30 and 7:20, location: AQ 3003 and AQ 3005</li> <li>I will confirm each midterm 1 week prior.</li> </ul> </li> </ul> </div>\n<h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Course Textbooks</span></h2>\n<div class=\"h2-box\">\n<ul class=\"ul-box\"> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Required Books</span>: none</li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Recommended Books</span>:\r			<ol> <li class=\"book\"><span class=\"book-title\">The Design of Everyday Things</span>\r				by Donald A. Norman, Basic Books, 2002, ISBN 9780465067107</li> <li class=\"book\"><span class=\"book-title\">User Interface Design and Evaluation</span>\r				by Stone, Jarrett, Woodroffe, and Minocha, Morgan Kaufmann, 2005, ISBN 9780120884360</li> <li class=\"book\"><span class=\"book-title\">Usability Engineering: Process, Products, and Examples</span>\r				by Leventhal and Barnes, Pearson Prentice-Hall, 2008, ISBN 9780131570085</li> </ol> </li> <li class=\"box-item\"><span class=\"box-item-text\">Reference Books</span>: none</li>\n</ul> </div> <h2><span class=\"h2-text\">Academic Honesty Statement</span></h2> <div class=\"h2-box\"> <p class=\"box-content\">Academic honesty plays a key role in our efforts to maintain a high standard of academic excellence and integrity.\r	Students are advised that <em>all</em> acts of intellectual dishonesty will be handled in accordance with the \r	<a href=\"http://www.sfu.ca/policies/Students/index.html\">SFU Academic Honesty and Student Conduct Policies</a>.</p> </div> </div>\n<!-- FOOTER --> <div id=\"footer\">\n<p class=\"footer-text\">Copyright Â© <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/\">School of Computing Science</a>,\r\n\r\n <a href=\"http://www.sfu.ca/\">Simon Fraser University</a>, \r\n\r\n <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/fas-info/cs/people/Faculty/Profile/alavergn.html\">Anne Lavergne</a> - Spring 2013 - This web site is \r\n  constantly being modified, so keep an eye on it!</p>\n</div>\n</body> </html>\n','2013-04-01 05:36:40.387519'),('http://www.cs.sfu.ca/CourseCentral/379/shermer/','CMPT 379 Home','<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN\" \"http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd\">\n\n<html xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">\n<!-- DW6 -->\n<head>\n<!-- Copyright 2005 Macromedia, Inc. All rights reserved. -->\n<title>CMPT 379 Home</title>\n<meta content=\"text/html; charset=utf-8\" http-equiv=\"Content-Type\"/>\n<link href=\"resources/compilers.css\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\"/>\n<script language=\"JavaScript\" type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n//--------------- LOCALIZEABLE GLOBALS ---------------\r\nvar d=new Date();\r\nvar monthname=new Array(\"January\",\"February\",\"March\",\"April\",\"May\",\"June\",\"July\",\"August\",\"September\",\"October\",\"November\",\"December\");\r\n//Ensure correct for language. English is \"January 1, 2004\"\r\nvar TODAY = monthname[d.getMonth()] + \" \" + d.getDate() + \", \" + d.getFullYear();\r\n//---------------   END LOCALIZEABLE   ---------------\r\n</script>\n<style type=\"text/css\">\r\n&lt;!--\r\ndiv.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:\"