a></div>\n<h1 id=\"PageTitle\">Course Outline - CMPT 225 - Data Structures and Programming</h1>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Information</h2>\n<div>\n<div style=\"float:left; width:200px;\">\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Subject</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Catalog Number</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Section</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Semester</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Title</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Instructor(s)</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Campus</p>\n</div>\n<div style=\"padding-left:20px;\">\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">CMPT</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">225</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">D100</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">2013 Summer (1134)</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">Data Structures and Programming</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:.5em;\">\n                    Anne Lavergne Â Â \n                \n			</p>\n<p style=\"padding-bottom:5px;\">Burnaby Mountain Campus</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Calendar Objective/Description</h2>\n<p>Introduction to a variety of practical and important data structures and methods for implementation and for experimental and analytical evaluation. Topics include: stacks, queues and lists; search trees; hash tables and algorithms; efficient sorting; object-oriented programming; time and space efficiency analysis; and experimental evaluation. </p>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Instructor\'s Objectives</h2>\n<p style=\"LastSection\">This course will explore ideas of data and program organization that allow complex tasks to be solved in simple and elegant ways. In order to manage the complexity of programs, we will consider abstract data types, including their concepts and implementations in Java.</p>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<p style=\"LastSection\"> MACM 101 and one of CMPT 125, 126 or 128; or CMPT 128 and approval as a Biomedical Engineering Major. Quantitative.</p>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Topics</h2>\n<ul> <li>Abstract data types: modularization, encapsulation, information hiding.</li>\n<li>Data structures: strings, sets, stacks, queues, lists, hash tables, trees, graphs (if time).</li>\n<li>Algorithms: recursion, searching and sorting, time and space efficiency analysis.</li>\n<li>Programming: Object-oriented design &amp; programming in support of extensible systems and software reuse. </li></ul>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Grading</h2>\n<p>     Grading will be based on a combination of assignments, lab exercises, quizzes and/or midterm exam(s), and a final examination. Details will be announced in the first lecture of the semester.</p>\n<p style=\"LastSection\">Students must attain an overall passing \n        grade on the weighted average of exams in the course in order to \n        obtain a clear pass (C- or better).</p>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Required Books</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Data Abstraction &amp; Problem Solving with Java - Walls and Mirrors (3e), F. M. Carrano &amp; J. J. Prichard, Addison Wesley, 2010, 9780132122306, most recent edition </li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"ParagraphTitle\">Academic Honesty Statement</h2>\n<p>Academic honesty plays a key role in our efforts to maintain a high standard of academic excellence and integrity. Students are advised that ALL acts of intellectual dishonesty will be handled in accordance with the SFU Academic Honesty and Student Conduct Policies ( http://www.sfu.ca/policies/gazette/student.html ).</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"last_updated_block\"> Data Last Updated:  </div>\n</div>\n<div>\n    Â \n</div>\n<div style=\"clear:both; \"></div>\n</div> <!-- end the two_col_container  -->\n<!-- The following code is for the SFU grey footer bar  -->\n<div id=\"footer\">\n\n            8888 University Drive, Burnaby, B.C. Canada V5A 1S6 |\n            <a href=\"http://www.sfu.ca/webmaster/terms.html\">Terms / Privacy</a> |\n            <a href=\"http://www.cs.sfu.ca/AboutCMPT/contacts.html\">Con